<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Afternoon news bits from Abashi</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=126971" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <blockquote>
<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/036639.html">Abashi, technical question about healers and pet classes..please respond =)</a><P>

As any seasoned healer will tell you, the F1-F8 keys are a neccessity. Targeting your players with these keys are a must. Since we can heal pets i was wondering if it were possible for clerics to hit the Fkeys twice to target a mage's(or any pet class)pet. I also play a magician and i am able to target myself with F1 and then press F1 again and it targets my pet. I dont think this is to unreasonable a request. It would just make it alot easier to monitor the health of a pet in a group situation. =)<P>

<B>It's a good idea, and I'll mention it, but I imagine that this might be a bit difficult to implement at this time. What the F-keys do is client-side, and the client really doesn't know who's pet is who's.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<Hr align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/037815.html">A Compelling Reason</a><P>

This is NOT a class envy post. I just want to thank you, Gordon, for supplying us with the answer to the basic question of "what makes a class ballanced?" I, for one, think that you and Verant are using entirely the wrong yardstick to measure ballance, but at least I understand where you are coming from when you say class x, y, or z is in fact ballanced in spite of my opinions and observations otherwise.<P>

<B>I respect your opinion, and thank you for voicing it, however it is very important that everyone is aware that balance does not equal equality in all things. The pinnacle of a good class-based system is interdependence, and homogenization of the classes doesn't promote that.</B><P>

1. Is there any available information as to how many characters of each class exist in Norrath?<P>

2. Is there comparitive information as to the number of class-hours each class has since the game began (I know, this is a bit much, but I want to know if the 8.6% of the existing characters that are of class X are actually played or just hold twink items, etc.)<P>

<B>We have access to the information, but it's not something that we'd generally release in a tabulated form. One thing I should mention is that we had no expectation that the number of characters in game would be spread across the classes evenly. This can easily be illustrated on the group level. For instance, there is no point of diminishing returns when adding warriors to a group. In other words, the benefit to the group that one warrior adds can always be doubled by adding another. Some other classes can't do that. For instance, adding a second bard to your group will not do as much as adding the first one did.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/037950.html">PKed in a bank and nothing can be done about it?</a><P>

First off, let me explain how this happened. I play on Rallos Zek, and have a high level Druid character there (49th level). This evening I was clearing out my bank account in Rivervale when I get a tell from another player (a Gnome named Castin) asking if I'd be interested in buying a belt item for Druids from him.<P>

Naturally curious, I took one step out the door and was hit with a Cancel Magic spell (Lost SoW and Skin Like Nature, SLN may have been gone already, not sure about this.) A split second later, Ice Comet hit me, I was dead as just as I turned to retreat back inside. (the Comet slingers name was Brann).<P>

[Snip text and a log]<P>

<B>I've read this over, and chatted with the customer service folk just to make sure rules haven't changed since I guided on a PvP server, but there doesn't appear to be anything "illegal" here.<P>
 
There's no rule baring someone from attacking you in town. The only thing that is illegal in regards to anything of this sort would be exploiting guard range issues, such as attacking someone in guard range while you are out of that range. If you get into a situation where the guards like your attacker more than they like you, it's feasible that you could be killed in town.<P> 

Here is sounds like they just sniped you while you were coming out of the bank.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038039.html">Ruining the Game to Prevent Twinking?</a><P>

Before the release of ROK there was a post by someone on the Verant staff stating that basically EQ does not have the best stats system, and that the effects of stats have been purposefully minimized to reduce the the effects of twinking. <P>

<B>I don't recall anyone saying that. What I do recall saying is that the reason we don't have any +skill items out there was to reduce the impact of twinking. Stats really don't affect twinking as their effect is scaled based upon the level of the recipient. For instance, a level 1 wizards with 200 INT has roughly 1 mana point more mana than one with 100 INT.<P> 

One other thing, I've seen a rumor going around that the effects of stats were drastically reduced at some point in late beta. Nothing like that happened.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038138.html">Hotkeys Don't Work While Medding. Bug?</a><P>

I'm just curious about the fact that pressing the keyboard shortcut for a hotkey doesn't work while medding. Is this a bug? You can press the hotkey button with the mouse and that works fine. Is there any chance this could be fixed? My carpal tunnel syndrome is getting worse because of this 8-).<P>

<B>Since we allow the buttons to be pressed with the mouse, I'll check with the client programmer to see if we can also allow the key to be pressed as well.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038153.html">Idea for class communications</a><P>

Would it be possible, or difficult, to implement a way for members of a class to talk to each other over a channel (like guildtalk). I think this could be useful for players communicating with others in their class regarding quests, strategy, exchange of research components, etc. e.g. /class Anyone have any information on the spell call of bones?<P>

<B>Blanket communication channels tend to reduce the sense of community in game, rather than enhance it. Instead of dealing with a specific person, and forming a relationship with them, it ends up pretty cold. This is somewhat apparent with zone-wide communications such as /shout and /ooc, however it's not as bad as a server-wide mechanism would be. In addition to this, there are some technical issues surrounding this idea (e.g. the number of additional packets to broadcast) which make the idea unattractive.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038164.html">For all those who had complaints about Kunark drops</a><P>

With good random drops, casual players could get nice items. No more camping a cyclops for 3 days, or having to pray that no one in one of the 3 uberguilds involved on a dragon hunt needs one of the items. No more 10 hour Fear and Hate breaks, which made it impossible for casual gamers to advance.<P>

<B>The updates that we made to item drop percentages and locations were not directly based upon complaints from people about loot being too comon, but rather economic reports that we run to determine the health of the economy and the rates at which items enter the world.<P>
 
Basically, once we got 100K people over in Kunark, we'd have found the problems regardless, so it isn't the "fault" of the players who brought the issue to public light.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038169.html">Compass training</a><P>

Why can't a person raise their sense heading skill faster if they have a compass? It is completely logical that you could increase a skill faster if you have an immediate way of checking it.<P>

<B>Well we don't have any way that we could easily implement skill-increase potential based on what is in your inventory on a per-skill basis. I suggest you train the skill up a bit. The way skill increases work is that they require a successful skill check before they'll roll for a skill increase.<P>
 
-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038170.html">Spell effects, timings, and how they should be changed.</a><P>

Just the other day I was playing on The Rathe and surprisingly(cough cough) the entire server kept getting horrible lag spikes. You would fight for ten minutes and then stand helplessly for five minutes while the spike hit. The good thing about this is that it effected the entire server, including mobs. It seems to me that a buffing spells' duration is based on RL time and not game time. Could we perhaps have the dev team look into this? It is a misfortunate situation when you have sow and your being chased by a Griff, spike hits, nothing is moving, five minutes later sow fades, spike disappears and the griff can now overtake you.<P>

<B>There's really no situation that could cause everything on the server (including NPCs) to "hang" for an amount of time. If there was a network connection issue, PCs could lag, however NPCs would go about their normal business. If it were a server problem, it wouldn't affect everyone on the server, just everyone in a particular zone.<P>
 
If the server were to have a problem causing the zone to hang for a bit, spells ticks wouldn't expire either. I imagine what happened in your case was a network problem.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038174.html">More buttons please.......</a><P>

Would it be possible to add another bank of six programmable buttons on the bottom right side of the screen?<P>

<B>Not at this juncture, no. Don't forget that the current bank of hotboxes do have six pages that you can put things on.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
